Definition 10. A Lie 3-algebra is a linear 2-category $L$ endowed with a bracket, i.e. an antisymmetric bilinear 2-functor $[-,-]:L\times L\to L$, which verifies the Jacobi identity up to a Jacobiator, i.e. a skew-symmetric trilinear natural 2-transformation $J_{xyz}:[[x,y],z]\rightarrow[[x,z],y]+[x,[y,z]],$ $x,y,z\in L_{0}$, which in turn satisfies the Baez-Crans Jacobiator identity up to an Identiator, i.e. a skew-symmetric quadrilinear 2-modification $\mathchar 28950\relax_{xyzu}:[J_{x,y,z},1_{u}]\circ_{0}(J_{[x,z],y,u}+J_{x,[y,% z],u})\circ_{0}([J_{xzu},1_{y}]+1)\circ_{0}([1_{x},J_{yzu}]+1)$ $\Rightarrow J_{[x,y],z,u}\circ_{0}([J_{xyu},1_{z}]+1)\circ_{0}(J_{x,[y,u],z}+J% _{[x,u],y,z}+J_{x,y,[z,u]}),$ $x,y,z,u\in L_{0}$, required to verify the coherence law $\mathchar 28939\relax_{1}+\mathchar 28939\relax_{4}^{-1}=\mathchar 28939\relax% _{3}+\mathchar 28939\relax_{2}^{-1},$ where $\mathchar 28939\relax_{1}$ – $\mathchar 28939\relax_{4}$ are explicitly given in Definitions 12 – 15 and where superscript $-1$ denotes the inverse for composition along a 1-cell.
Definition 6. Let $L$, $L^{\prime}$, and $L^{\prime\prime}$ be linear $2$-categories. A bilinear 2-functor $F:L\times L^{\prime}\to L^{\prime\prime}$ is a $2$-functor such that $F:L_{m}\times L^{\prime}_{m}\to L^{\prime\prime}_{m}$ is bilinear for all $m\in\{0,1,2\}$.
Definition 12. The first 2-cell $\mathchar 28939\relax_{1}$ is given by $\mathchar 28939\relax_{1}=1_{11}\circ_{0}\left(\mathchar 28950\relax_{x,y,z,[u% ,v]}+[\mathchar 28950\relax_{xyzv},1^{2}_{u}]\right)\circ_{0}1_{12}\circ_{0}% \left(\mathchar 28950\relax_{[x,v],y,z,u}+\mathchar 28950\relax_{x,[y,v],z,u}+% \mathchar 28950\relax_{x,y,[z,v],u}+1^{2}\right),$ where $1_{11}=1_{J_{[[x,y],z],u,v}},1_{12}=1_{[J_{x,[z,v],y},1_{u}]+[J_{[x,v],z,y},1_% {u}]+[J_{x,z,[y,v]},1_{u}]}+1^{2},$ and where the $1^{2}$ are the identity 2-cells associated with the elements of $L_{0}$ provided by the composability condition.
Definition 1. An $\mathbf{n}$-globular vector space $L$, $n\in\mathbb{N}$, is a sequence $L_{n}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle s,t}}{{\rightrightarrows}}L_{n-1}\stackrel{{% \scriptstyle s,t}}{{\rightrightarrows}}\ldots\stackrel{{\scriptstyle s,t}}{{% \rightrightarrows}}L_{0}\rightrightarrows 0,$ of vector spaces $L_{m}$ and linear maps $s,t$ such that $s(s(a))=s(t(a))\;\;\mbox{and}\;\;t(s(a))=t(t(a)),$ for any $a\in L_{m},$ $m\in\{1,\ldots,n\}$. The maps $s,t$ are called source map and target map, respectively, and any element of $L_{m}$ is an m-cell.
Definition 3. A linear n-functor $F:L\to L^{\prime}$ between two linear $n$-categories is made up by linear maps $F:L_{m}\to L^{\prime}_{m}$, $m\in\{0,\ldots,n\}$, such that the categorical structure – source and target maps, composition maps, identity maps – is respected.
