Definition 4.41 The two-sided dual Koszul resolution of $\mathscr{P}^{\bot}$ is the dual standard construction applied to the classifying morphism $\kappa_{\mathscr{P}}$: $T(\mathscr{P})=\mathscr{P}^{\bot}\circ_{\kappa_{\mathscr{P}}}\mathscr{P}\circ_% {\kappa_{\mathscr{P}}}\mathscr{P}^{\bot},$ which is a $\mathscr{P}^{\bot}$-bicomodule.
Definition 2.12. For any ${\mathcal{M}}\in\operatorname{silt}\nolimits{\mathcal{T}}$, we define a subcategory of ${\mathcal{T}}$ by ${\mathcal{T}}_{{\mathcal{M}}}^{\leq 0}:=\{X\in{\mathcal{T}}\ |\ \operatorname{% Hom}\nolimits_{{\mathcal{T}}}({\mathcal{M}},X[>0])=0\}.$ We put ${\mathcal{T}}_{{\mathcal{M}}}^{\leq\ell}={\mathcal{T}}_{{\mathcal{M}}}^{<\ell+% 1}:={\mathcal{T}}_{{\mathcal{M}}}^{\leq 0}[-\ell]$ for $\ell\in\mathbb{Z}$.
Definition 2.1. Let ${\mathcal{M}}$ be a subcategory of a triangulated category ${\mathcal{T}}$. (a) We say that ${\mathcal{M}}$ is silting if $\operatorname{Hom}\nolimits_{{\mathcal{T}}}({\mathcal{M}},{\mathcal{M}}[>0])=0$ and ${\mathcal{T}}=\mathsf{thick}{\mathcal{M}}$. We denote by $\operatorname{silt}\nolimits{\mathcal{T}}$ the collection of silting subcategories in ${\mathcal{T}}$. (b) We say that ${\mathcal{M}}$ is tilting if $\operatorname{Hom}\nolimits_{{\mathcal{T}}}({\mathcal{M}},{\mathcal{M}}[\neq 0% ])=0$ and ${\mathcal{T}}=\mathsf{thick}{\mathcal{M}}$. (c) We say that an object $M\in{\mathcal{T}}$ is silting (respectively, tilting) if so is $\mathsf{add}M$.
Definition 2.6. Let $\ell$ be an integer. We call a $k$-linear $\operatorname{Hom}\nolimits$-finite triangulated category ${\mathcal{T}}$ $\ell$-Calabi-Yau if there is a bifunctorial isomorphism ${\rm{Hom}}_{{\mathcal{T}}}(-,?)\simeq D{\rm{Hom}}_{{\mathcal{T}}}(?,-[\ell])$.
Definition 2.10. For ${\mathcal{M}},{\mathcal{N}}\in\operatorname{silt}\nolimits{\mathcal{T}}$, we write ${\mathcal{M}}\geq{\mathcal{N}}$ if $\operatorname{Hom}\nolimits_{{\mathcal{T}}}({\mathcal{M}},{\mathcal{N}}[>0])=0$.
Definition 1.4. Let ${\mathcal{T}}$ be a triangulated category and $({\mathcal{X}},{\mathcal{Y}})$ a pair of subcategories of ${\mathcal{T}}$. • We say that $({\mathcal{X}},{\mathcal{Y}})$ is a torsion pair if $\operatorname{Hom}\nolimits_{{\mathcal{T}}}({\mathcal{X}},{\mathcal{Y}})=0$ and ${\mathcal{X}}*{\mathcal{Y}}={\mathcal{T}}$. • We say that $({\mathcal{X}},{\mathcal{Y}})$ is a t-structure [BBD] if $({\mathcal{X}}[1],{\mathcal{Y}})$ is a torsion pair and ${\mathcal{X}}[1]\subset{\mathcal{X}}$. In this case ${\mathcal{X}}\cap{\mathcal{Y}}$ is called the heart. • We say that $({\mathcal{X}},{\mathcal{Y}})$ is a co-t-structure [P1] if $({\mathcal{X}}[-1],{\mathcal{Y}})$ is a torsion pair and ${\mathcal{X}}\subset{\mathcal{X}}[1]$. In this case ${\mathcal{X}}\cap{\mathcal{Y}}$ is called the coheart. • We say that a torsion pair $({\mathcal{X}},{\mathcal{Y}})$ is a stable t-structure [M] if ${\mathcal{X}}={\mathcal{X}}[1]$.
Definition 3.1. a round filter $F$ is called prime if, for any finite set $A\subseteq L$, $\bigvee A\in F$ implies $A\cap F\neq\emptyset$.
Definition 1.18. A non-empty subset $I\subseteq L$ of a proximity lattice $(\mathbb{L},R)$ is called a round ideal (sometimes $R$-ideal), if it is • $R$-downward closed: for any $b\in I$, if $aRb$, then $a\in I$. • $R$-updirected: for any $a,b\in I$, there is $c\in I$ such that $aRc$ and $bRc$. Dually, a round filter (or $R$-filter), is a subset $F$ of $L$ which is $R$-upward closed and $R$-downdirected.
Definition 3.7. A spectral proximity space is a pair $(X,f)$, where $X$ is a spectral space and $f$ is a continuous retraction. A continuous proximity function from a spectral proximity space $(X,f)$ to a spectral proximity space $(X^{\prime},f^{\prime})$ is a continuous function $g:X\to X^{\prime}$ such that $f^{\prime}g=g=gf$: We denote the category of spectral proximity spaces with continuous proximity functions by $\mathsf{SpecPrSp}$.
Definition 2.2. Let $(\mathbb{L},R)$ be a proximity lattice and $h:\mathbb{L}\to\mathbb{C}$ an extension. We call $u\in\mathbb{C}$ a round ideal element (or round-open) if there is a round ideal $I$ of $L$ such that $u=\bigvee h[I]$. Dually, $u$ is a round filter element (or round-closed) if there is a round filter $F$ of $L$ such that $u=\bigwedge h[F]$. We denote the set of round ideal elements of the extension $h$ by $\mathcal{I}_{R}^{h}(\mathbb{C})$, and the set of round filter elements by $\mathcal{F}_{R}^{h}(\mathbb{C})$ (or, when the map $h$ is fixed, we just write $\mathcal{I}_{R}(\mathbb{C})$ and $\mathcal{F}_{R}(\mathbb{C})$). We say a function $h:\mathbb{L}\to\mathbb{C}$ is a $\pi$-canonical extension of the proximity lattice $(\mathbb{L},R)$ if 1. ($R$-dense) For all $u,v\in\mathbb{C}$, if $u\nleq v$, then there exist a round filter element $x$ and a round ideal element $y$ such that $x\leq u$, $v\leq y$, and $x\nleq y$ in $\mathbb{C}$. 2. ($R$-compact) For any subsets $S,T\subseteq L$ such that $\bigwedge h[R[S]]\leq\bigvee h[R^{-1}[T]]$ in $\mathbb{C}$, there are finite sets $S^{\prime}\subseteq S$ and $T^{\prime}\subseteq T$ such that $\bigwedge S^{\prime}R\bigvee T^{\prime}$ in $\mathbb{L}$. 3. ($R$-join-preserving) For all $a\in\mathbb{L}$, $h(a)=\bigvee\{h(b)\ |\ bRa\}$. Dually, $k:\mathbb{L}\to\mathbb{C}$ is a $\sigma$-canonical extension of the proximity lattice $(\mathbb{L},R)$ if it satisfies items 1 and 2 above, and 3’: 3’. ($R$-meet-preserving) For all $a\in\mathbb{L}$, $k(a)=\bigwedge\{k(b)\ |\ aRb\}$.
Definition 1.1. Let $X$ be a topological space. A set $S\subseteq X$ is called saturated if it is an intersection of opens, and compact if any open cover of $S$ contains a finite subcover. The space $X$ is called 1. locally compact if, for any open neighbourhood $U$ of a point $x\in X$, there exists an open set $V$ and a compact set $K$ such that $x\in V\subseteq K\subseteq U$. 2. sober if the assignment $x\mapsto\{U\subseteq X\text{ open}\ |\ x\in U\}$ is surjective onto the set of completely prime filters of the frame of opens of $X$, and $T_{0}$ if this assignment is injective. 3. stably compact if $X$ is $T_{0}$, sober, locally compact, and the collection $\mathsf{KS}(X)$ of compact-saturated sets is closed under finite intersections. 4. spectral if $X$ is $T_{0}$, sober and the collection $\mathsf{KO}(X)$ of compact-open sets forms a basis for the open sets which is closed under finite intersections. Note that a spectral space is always stably compact.
Definition 2.12. Let $T^{\pi}:\mathcal{I}_{R}((\mathbb{L},R)^{\pi})\to\mathcal{I}_{R}((\mathbb{M},S)% ^{\pi})$ be defined, for $y$ a round ideal element, by $T^{\pi}(y):=\bigvee\{h_{\mathbb{M}}(b)\ |\ b\in\mathbb{M}\text{ s.t. }\exists a% \in\mathbb{L}:aTb\text{ and }h_{\mathbb{L}}(a)\leq y\}.$ Now let $T^{\pi}:(\mathbb{L},R)^{\pi}\to(\mathbb{M},S)^{\pi}$ be the function defined by $T^{\pi}(u):=\bigwedge\{T^{\pi}(y):u\leq y\in\mathcal{I}_{R}((\mathbb{L},R)^{% \pi})\}.$ Dually, we could define the $\sigma$-extension of an $m$-morphism $U$ between meet-strong proximity lattices.
Definition 1.2. A proximity lattice is a pair $(\mathbb{L},R)$, where $\mathbb{L}=(L,\vee,\wedge,\bot,\top)$ is a lattice and $R\subseteq L\times L$ is a relation satisfying the following axioms: 1. $R\circ R=R$, 2. For any finite set $A\subseteq L$ and $b\in L$, $\bigvee A\,R\,b\iff\forall a\in A\,aRb$. 3. For any finite set $B\subseteq L$ and $a\in L$, $a\,R\,\bigwedge B\iff\forall b\in B\,aRb$. A proximity lattice is called join-strong if, furthermore, 4. For any finite set $B\subseteq L$ and $a\in L$, if $a\,R\,\bigvee B$, then there is a finite set $B^{\prime}\subseteq R^{-1}[B]$ such that $a\,R\,\bigvee B^{\prime}$. Dually, a proximity lattice is called meet-strong if 5. For any finite set $A\subseteq L$ and $b\in L$, if $\bigwedge A\,R\,b$, then there is a finite set $A^{\prime}\subseteq R[A]$ such that $\bigwedge A^{\prime}\,R\,b$. A proximity lattice is doubly strong if it is both join-strong and meet-strong. We call a relation $R$ on a lattice increasing if $aRb$ implies $a\leq b$. In the original definition of Jung and Sünderhauf, it was emphasized that the relation $R$ of a proximity lattice does not need to be increasing. However, as we will see below, the assumption that the relation is increasing does not change the category of proximity lattices, up to equivalence, and makes the ensuing theory quite a bit cleaner and easier to present. We will come back to this point in Remark 1.23. This definition of proximity lattice is close to, but a bit more general than that of Jung and Sünderhauf [21]. Note in particular that the ‘proximity lattices’ of Jung and Sünderhauf are what we will call ‘distributive proximity lattices’. The idea of using distributive proximity lattices to represent stably compact spaces is already present in Smyth [26], but he did not assume both ‘strong’ axioms (4) and (5) for his structures.
Definition 1.9. Let $(\mathbb{L},R)$ and $(\mathbb{M},S)$ be proximity lattices. A proximity relation between $(\mathbb{L},R)$ and $(\mathbb{M},S)$ is a relation $G\subseteq L\times M$ which satisfies the following conditions: 1. $G\circ S=G$, 2. $R\circ G=G$, 3. For any finite set $A\subseteq L$ and $b\in M$, $\bigvee A\,G\,b\iff\forall a\in A\,aGb.$ 4. For any finite set $B\subseteq M$ and $a\in L$, $a\,G\,\bigwedge B\iff\forall b\in B\,aGb.$ The relation $G$ is called join-approximable if, furthermore 4. For any finite set $B\subseteq M$ and $a\in L$, if $a\,G\,\bigvee B$, then there is a finite set $A\subseteq G^{-1}[B]$ such that $a\,R\,\bigvee A$. Dually, $G$ is called meet-approximable if 5. For any finite set $A\subseteq L$ and $b\in M$, if $\bigwedge A\,G\,b$, then there is a finite set $B\subseteq G[A]$ such that $\bigwedge B\,S\,b$. A proximity morphism from a proximity lattice $(\mathbb{L},R)$ to a proximity lattice $(\mathbb{M},S)$ is a relation $H\subseteq L\times M$ such that the relation $H^{-1}\subseteq M\times L$ is a proximity relation. If $H^{-1}$ is furthermore join-approximable (meet-approximable), then we call $H$ a j-morphism (m-morphism).
